I went back and tried to find the history of the change that added `UNSECURE_TRAFFIC_MANAGED_BY_STACK_ENABLE` behavior.
- Seems like it was added from https://github.com/openthread/openthread/pull/4782
- Here is the related code, which disables link security on an IPv6 message when the port matches even if security is explicitly requested for message the tx (by the caller): 
```c++
        if (aFromNcpHost && (nextHeader == kProtoTcp || nextHeader == kProtoUdp))
        {
            uint16_t sourcePort, destPort;

            SuccessOrExit(error = aMessage.Read(aMessage.GetOffset(), sourcePort));
            SuccessOrExit(error = aMessage.Read(aMessage.GetOffset() + sizeof(sourcePort), destPort));
            sourcePort = HostSwap16(sourcePort);
            destPort   = HostSwap16(destPort);

            //...

#if OPENTHREAD_CONFIG_UNSECURE_TRAFFIC_MANAGED_BY_STACK_ENABLE
            // check whether source port is an unsecure port
            if (Get<Filter>().IsUnsecurePort(sourcePort))
            {
                aMessage.SetLinkSecurityEnabled(false);
                otLogInfoIp6("Disabled link security for packet to %s", header.GetDestination().ToString().AsCString());
            }
#else
            OT_UNUSED_VARIABLE(sourcePort);
#endif
        }
```
- Thinking more on this, I don't think we want to relax and apply this rule to all IPv6 message.
- **I actually favor removing this whole feature `UNSECURE_TRAFFIC_MANAGED_BY_STACK_ENABLE`** (I had some concerns about this earlier -> https://github.com/openthread/openthread/pull/4782#discussion_r404992091)
- I don't recall why we needed this behavior. Probably for weave pairing. I think if there is such a use-case it would be better to manage it at the next layer and not add this in OT core(i.e., it is the job of the next layer to decide whether it wants to enable link security for an IPv6 message it is passing to Thread stack). If I recall correctly, that was how weave pairing worked with `wpantund`.

