Actually, super-calls should work, no?  I haven't actually looked at the details of which class implements what (so I may be misunderstanding your problem), but say you have
```
 Base
 /  \
B   C
 \ /
  D
```
and all 4 methods implement `foo` (i.e. `_initialize_sufficient_statistics`) with a super()-call (except for `Base`; this is important so that we don't end up trying calling the non-existent `object.foo()`):
```
class Base:
    def foo(self):
        print("base")
class A(Base):
    def foo(self):
        print("a"); return super().foo()
class B(Base):
    def foo(self):
        print("b"); return super().foo()
class C(A, B):
    def foo(self):
        print("c"); return super().foo()
```
then `C().foo()` will actually execute all four method bodies (printing `c a b base` -- note that the order of inheritance ends up determining whether A.foo or B.foo is called first).  (See e.g. http://python-history.blogspot.com/2010/06/method-resolution-order.html; also note that the old Py2 super-syntax, while longer, was clearer here: the result of the super-call in a method body actually depends on the exact type of `self`, not just what class we are currently in).

Or did I completely misunderstand your point?

